#Text=LXI
#Text=He saw her then every day .

#Text=He began going to lunch at the shop , but Mildred stopped him : she said it made the girls talk ; so he had to content himself with tea ; but he always waited about to walk with her to the station ; and once or twice a week they dined together .
#Text=He gave her little presents , a gold bangle , gloves , handkerchiefs , and the like .
#Text=He was spending more than he could afford , but he could not help it : it was only when he gave her anything that she showed any affection .
#Text=She knew the price of everything , and her gratitude was in exact proportion with the value of his gift .
#Text=He did not care .
#Text=He was too happy when she volunteered to kiss him to mind by what means he got her demonstrativeness .
#Text=He discovered that she found Sundays at home tedious , so he went down to Herne Hill in the morning , met her at the end of the road , and went to church with her .
#Text=" I always like to go to church once , " she said .
#Text=" It looks well , does n't it ? "
#Text=Then she went back to dinner , he got a scrappy meal at a hotel , and in the afternoon they took a walk in Brockwell Park .
#Text=They had nothing much to say to one another , and Philip , desperately afraid she was bored ( she was very easily bored ) , racked his brain for topics of conversation .
#Text=He realised that these walks amused neither of them , but he could not bear to leave her , and did all he could to lengthen them till she became tired and out of temper .
#Text=He knew that she did not care for him , and he tried to force a love which his reason told him was not in her nature : she was cold .
#Text=He had no claim on her , but he could not help being exacting .
#Text=Now that they were more intimate he found it less easy to control his temper ; he was often irritable and could not help saying bitter things .
#Text=Often they quarrelled , and she would not speak to him for a while ; but this always reduced him to subjection , and he crawled before her .
#Text=He was angry with himself for showing so little dignity .
#Text=He grew furiously jealous if he saw her speaking to any other man in the shop , and when he was jealous he seemed to be beside himself .
#Text=He would deliberately insult her , leave the shop and spend afterwards a sleepless night tossing on his bed , by turns angry and remorseful .
#Text=Next day he would go to the shop and appeal for forgiveness .
#Text=" Do n't be angry with me , " he said .
#Text=" I 'm so awfully fond of you that I ca n't help myself . "
#Text=" One of these days you 'll go too far , " she answered .
#Text=He was anxious to come to her home in order that the greater intimacy should give him an advantage over the stray acquaintances she made during her working-hours ; but she would not let him .
#Text=" My aunt would think it so funny , " she said .
#Text=He suspected that her refusal was due only to a disinclination to let him see her aunt .
#Text=Mildred had represented her as the widow of a professional man ( that was her formula of distinction ) , and was uneasily conscious that the good woman could hardly be called distinguished .
#Text=Philip imagined that she was in point of fact the widow of a small tradesman .
#Text=He knew that Mildred was a snob .
#Text=But he found no means by which he could indicate to her that he did not mind how common the aunt was .
#Text=Their worst quarrel took place one evening at dinner when she told him that a man had asked her to go to a play with him .
#Text=Philip turned pale , and his face grew hard and stern .
#Text=" You 're not going ? " he said .
#Text=" Why should n't I ?

column1: #Text=" If you knew how happy just one word would make me ! "
#Text=" Well , what I always say is , people must take me as they find me , and if they do n't like it they can lump it . "
#Text=But sometimes she expressed herself more plainly still , and , when he asked the question , answered :
